962. In ruborem...dabo. Asin. 426 Iussin z'u splendorem dari bullas has foribus uostris ?‚ Pseud. 928 iu timorem dabo militarem aduenam, Asin. 574 Ubi saepe ad lanyuorem tua duritia dederis octo Vulz'dos lictores, Ter. Haut. 807 uel me haee deambulatio, Quam non laboriosa, ad lanquorem dedit. In a fragment of the Comedian Anaxandrides (22 K.) we have a similar threat (apparently of a master to a slave): Ἐρυθρότερον καρῖδος ὀπτῆς o·’ ἀποφανῶ.

964. Tandem, often in impatient comm-ands, eg. Mil. 1030 tandem ades, remele'gyo. Istaec aufer. Cam-e. 245 aufer istaev, quaeso, atque lzoe responde quod rogo, with that colloquial use of (aufer found in Hor. S. 11. vii. 43 avcfer *me vvultu terrere, Aul. 638 aufer cauillmn, Truc. 861 aufer uuyas. The change of dic of the MSS. into the older form dice would restore the metre of the 11116, but dice seems not to be used before an initial consonant by Plautus unless there is something of a pause after the word, eg. liud. 124 A. Tu siquid opus est, dice. B. Die quod te royo, Mil. 256 dice, monstra, praecipe (cf. ad v, 359). On the other hand the form ista calls for change. The rarity of the forms ista Nom., Ace. Plur. Neut., istud Nom., Acc. Sing. Neut. in Plautus and Terence has long excited the suspicion of editors. In Terence there is not a single occiurence of the Nom., Acc. Sing. Neut. of iste 111 which the form ‘istuc is not attested by at least the greater portion of the MSS„ and the same is true of the Nom. Aoo. Plur. form istaev, with the single exception of Adel. 677 Quoi ueneram (relucemus, sed quid ista, Aeschine, Nostra ?‚ where the chief MS„ the Bembinus‚ reads istie.
